INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, FABRICATION BAY 2 - DAY

A cathedral of a shop floor. Gantry cranes, weld curtains, a bell
nozzle the size of a grain silo up on stands. Two hundred workers in
company blues stand in loose ranks, hoods up, gloves off.

Among them: TITO ALVAREZ, 24, welding hood pushed back, a smear of
soot to the jaw.

At a portable lectern: MIRA VESS, 40s, charcoal suit, no notes.
Off her shoulder, ADMINISTRATOR PELL with a tablet, recording. At
the back of the ranks, MACK BOONE stands with his arms folded.

VESS:
I will not waste your morning. Under the Compliance Monitorship,
Frontier's fabrication footprint exceeds the mission profile the
government has assigned us. Effective today, Bay Two is closed.
Two hundred positions are eliminated.

Silence. Then a stir through the ranks, voices low and getting less
low.

WORKER:
My father cut the first nozzle ring in this bay!

VESS:
I know he did. His name is on the wall of the visitor center, where
tourists photograph it. This decision is mine. Not Magnus Hale's.
Mine. If you need somewhere to put that, put it on me.

She lets that sit. Nobody thanks her for it.

VESS:
Terms. Severance is twelve months at full rate. Health coverage
carries the same twelve. The tooling and heavy equipment will be
declared surplus and sold for scrap at public auction. Shop
inventory will be palletized and dispositioned by an outside
logistics contractor.

Mack, at the back, unfolds his arms.

VESS:
Last. Each of you carries a priority-rehire designation, should
operations resume. I do not expect you to believe that means
anything. Keep the card anyway.

She steps off the lectern. No questions invited, none asked. Pell
taps his tablet and leans toward her.

PELL:
For the record, the Monitorship views this as a — a meaningful
posture of alignment. I'll be noting the, ah, expedited timeline
favorably.

VESS:
Note whatever you like.

She walks the length of the bay to the doors, heels on concrete the
only sound, two hundred men watching her go.

LATER

The ranks have broken up. Men pack toolboxes. A news crew shoots
through the fence gate: workers filing out with toolboxes and milk
crates.

Tito stands at his station a last moment. On the bench: a practice
weld, two plates joined by a bead like a row of dimes. He raps it
twice with one knuckle, picks up his hood, and walks out past Mack.

MACK:
Alvarez.

TITO:
Mr. Boone.

MACK:
You paid up at the union hall?

TITO:
Through March.

MACK:
Keep it that way.

Tito looks at him. Mack is already looking at his clipboard. Tito
carries his toolbox out into the daylight.

Mack takes a small pocket notebook from his jacket, writes one line,
and puts it away.

CUT TO:
